description._value: Abstract Epistasis describes that mutations can have different effects in combination as they have individually. Here we show that the metabolic network, the largest biochemical system within the cell, is mediating epistatic genetic interactions affecting transcriptome, proteome and metabolome at a genome-wide scale. We interrupted four model metabolic pathways, histidine, leucine, methionine and uracil biosynthesis in all 16 possible combinations and complemented the deficiencies by external nutrition. Affecting growth linearly, the resultant metabolic reconfigurations caused differential expression of ⅔rd of transcriptome, altering transcriptional responses to an extent that the same gene deletion resulted in expression profiles possessing up to zero overlap. Only 5% of transcriptional events were linear and non-epistatic, 36% explained by genetic dominance while 35% were quantitatively epistatic. While epistatic transcripts could obtain all forms of epistasis, non-epistatic transcripts were encoded by genes more likely essential, more connected in protein-protein and genetic interaction networks and were evolutionarily more conserved. Protein levels responded similarly and correlated with the transcriptome qualitatively, quantitatively as well as in dynamic range. On the metabolic level, epistasis was not observed within central carbon metabolism, but intermediary metabolites, amino acids and redox cofactors responded so that in total metabolic epistasis exceeded that of transcriptome and proteome. Affecting all but the most connected genes, metabolic interactions result in epistasis across all molecular layers. Considering the size of the metabolic network, metabolism could thus be the most important cause of epistasis.

Pre-cultures of the S. cerevisiae strains were prepared in drop-in media (synthetic minimal media supplemented only with the nutrients to complement auxotrophic requirements) and cultured for 12-20 h in a 96-well plate (30°C, 250 rpm). Main-cultures were inoculated in fresh synthetic completed media and cultivation, sample collection, quenching and metabolite extraction were performed according  to(Ewald et. al., 2009 PMID: 19320491 ). Specifically, the yeast strains were cultured in 96-well fritted plates (1 strain per two wells) (Nunc, USA) with a 4mm glass bead in each well for mixing. For quenching a 48-well plate containing 3.6 mL -40°C quenching solution  (60% methanol, 10 mM NH4-acetate) per well was prepared and put into a vacuum manifold. Mid-exponential cultures were put on top of the 48-well plate and sucked into the quenching solution. The quenched cultures were centrifuged for 5 min at 4000 rpm -9°C and the supernatant was discarded. Subsequently, the plate with the cell pellets was transferred into a -50°C ethanol bath with dry ice.

The extraction protocol was adopted from Ewald et al., 2009 PMID: 19320491. Specifically, the cell pellets were resuspended in 1mL precooled extraction solution (75% ethanol, 10 mM NH4-acetate) and 50 µL 13C-yeast internal standard was added. To complete extraction, the plate was transferred into a 80°C water bath for 3 min with vortexing steps every 30-45 seconds. The extracts were stored at -80°C until they were dried over night with a vacuum centrifuge (Christ-RVC 2-33 CD plus, Kuehner AG, Switzerland).

LC-MS measurements were performed as described in Buescher et al., 2009 PMID: 20433152. Specifically, the dried extracts were dissolved in 50-100 uL ddH2O and 15 uL were injected for LC-MS analysis. The metabolites were separated with a Waters Acquity T3 end-capped reversed phase column (150mm x 2.1mm x 1.8 µm) on a Waters Acquity UPLC (Waters, Milford, MA, USA) system.

The mass spectrometry was performed as described in Buescher et al., 2009 PMID: 20433152. Specifically, for the detection of the metabolites we used a Thermo TSQ Quantum Ultra triple quadrupole mass spectrometer (Thermo Fisher Scientific, Waltham, MA, USA) with a heated electrospray ionization source in negative mode with single reaction monitoring. Peak integration was done with an in-house software (B. Begemann & N. Zamboni, unpublished). The metabolite peak areas were further normalized to the internal 13C internal standard and to biomass (OD600).

title._value: Metabolism triggers system-wide epistasis on transcriptome, proteome and metabolome
